Gierig’s edition (Leipsic 1800) with Latin notes is a thoroughly good book. A great part of the notes to this selection were prepared without consulting Gierig, but on comparison they will often be found to coincide.

The letters in this selection are not arranged chronolo- gically‚ but printed in the order in which they stand in the ordinary arrangement. The lines of each letter have been ⁸ numbered in the text to facilitate reference to the notes. Reference in the notes to a passage contained in this selection is made thus, Ep. a. 1, the first figure referring to the number of the letter in this selection‚ and the second figure to the line in the text. References to letters not in this selection are preceded by the abbreviation Bu, thuS, Bk. 3. 9. In these cases, the first figure gives the number of the Book according to the usual arrangement of the lettere, and the second figure the number of the letter. Book ro is referred to by the abbreviation Trai, thus Trai. 20. Frequent references have been made to Madvig's Latin Grammar (as Madv), which, with other references, and some of the notes themselves are addressed rather to the teacher than to the

pupil.
